  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a financial crime\n- Initial reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n2. 1980s Developments\n- Increased focus on drug-related financial crimes\n- Introduction of mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n\n3. Key Milestones\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- 1990: First international anti-money laundering standards\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded legal frameworks\n\n4. Modern Legislation\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Comprehensive beneficial ownership disclosure rules\n- Increased digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency transaction regulations\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Broader definitions of money laundering\n- More severe criminal penalties\n- Advanced technological detection mechanisms\n- Greater cross-border information sharing\n- Expanded regulatory scope beyond traditional financial institutions\n\n6. Global Compliance\n- Increasing standardization of international anti-money laundering regulations\n- Robust enforcement mechanisms\n- Continuous adaptation to emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legislative approach has become increasingly comprehensive and technologically sophisticated.",
